Three Murang&rsquo;a leaders have called on politicians and residents to remain peaceful and calm ahead of the Jubilee primaries slated for April 21.Jamleck Kamau (Kigumo MP), Deputy Governor Gakure Monyo and former Maragua MP Elias Mbau warned confrontational politics could spark chaos in the county.The Kigumo MP, who is eyeing Murang&rsquo;a governor seat, said the leaders should adhere to the peace pact they signed last month.&ldquo;We don&rsquo;t want to witness bloodshed or loss of property through violence as was the case after the 2007 general election,&rdquo; he said.Speaking at Sabasaba Catholic Church after mass on Sunday, Kamau said the Jubilee Party led by President Uhuru Kenyatta has laid down strategies to ensure there will be no violence during nominations. &ldquo;Even the President wants us to conduct mature politics and maintain peace,&rdquo; he said. &ldquo;Every leader causing divisions and animosity among residents should be voted out or be prevented from holding a public office at the ballot,&rdquo; Gakure said.The deputy governor called on residents to vote wisely and lock out chest thumping leaders.Mbau said Murang&rsquo;a has for decades been holding peaceful elections. He said the present incumbents who have panicked and are worried of losing their seats are the ones who areapplying hooliganism in their politics.Kigumo MP Jamleck Kamau, Deputy Governor Gakure Monyo and former Margua MP Elias Mbau asked aspirants to conduct peaceful campaigns. They said political fanaticism has become a trend. Mbau said they want leaders who will work together to bring development and improve the living standards of Murang&rsquo;a residents. Kamau criticised his rival&rsquo;s supporters who he alleged have been moving around the county convening meetings on his behalf.